# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: guernsey-australian-rules-football
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-canberra-p01] The league was founded as the **Federal Territory Australian Rules Football League** in 1924 with founding members Acton and Queanbeyan.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-canberra-p01] The following year, the premiership was contested by 4 clubs including Canberra, Federal and Duntroon.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-canberra-p01] By 1926 the competition had gained popularity and was contested by 5 clubs.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-canberra-p01] In November 2010 the five AFL Canberra Premier Division clubs merged with the Premier Division clubs of the Queensland Australian Football League to form the North East Australian Football League.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-canberra-p01] From 2011 onwards, the AFL Canberra Premier Division together with the reserve sides from the Sydney Swans and Greater Western Sydney Giants would form the NEAFL Eastern Conference.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-canberra-p01] However the NEAFL was later dissolved due primarily to the COVID pandemic and associated financial pressures.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-canberra-p01] The AFL Canberra has been through a number of forms.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-canberra-p01] Clubs listed by highest grade of competition.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-canberra-p01] Point colours indicate club's highest level of competition.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-queensland-women-s-league] The **Queensland Australian Football League Women's** (**QAFLW**) is the highest-level women's Australian rules football competition in Queensland.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-queensland-women-s-league] It provides elite women footballers the opportunity to play in a semi-professional environment.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-queensland-women-s-league] Many players from this league have represented their state, earned All-Australian honours, and participated in the AFL Women's (AFLW) competition.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-queensland-women-s-league] There are five senior women's Australian rules football leagues in Queensland governed by AFL Queensland.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-queensland-women-s-league] The second tier of women's football in South-East Queensland is the Queensland Football Association Women's (QFAW), which was introduced in 2017.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-queensland-women-s-league] This competition is designed to allow women who are new to the game to develop their football understanding and skills, and also provide new clubs with an entry point into women's football.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-queensland-women-s-league] The medal is awarded to the best and fairest player in the league, and was named after Brisbane player Emma Zielke in August 2021.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] The **AFL reserve grade competition**, commonly known simply as the **AFL reserves**, was an Australian rules football competition that operated as a second-tier competition to the Australian Football League (AFL) from 1919 until 1999.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] Prior to 1990, it was known as the **VFL reserve grade competition**, **VFL reserves** or **VFL seconds**.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] In its final season in 1999, the competition was made up of the reserves teams of all the senior AFL clubs that were based in Victoria, plus that of the Sydney Swans.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] Since 2000, the Victorian Football League (VFL), formerly known as the Victorian Football Association (VFA), has operated as a hybrid second-tier senior competition and reserves competition for most of the AFL clubs.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] In 1919, a new football competition known as the **Victorian Junior Football League** (**VJFL**) was established – at this time, junior was the term used for open age football of a lower standard than senior football, rather than for under age football.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] The league was intended to bring a junior club affiliated with each of the Victorian Football League (VFL) senior clubs into a single competition, and to adopt the same district eligibility scheme which the VFL had introduced in 1916.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] Player permit rules allowed for automatic transfers between the junior and senior clubs until July, allowing the juniors to serve as second eighteens for the seniors.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] The junior and senior clubs shared a home ground, with the juniors playing home when the seniors played away.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] University, which had left the VFL senior competition after 1914, also entered a stand-alone junior team in the competition.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] Shortly before the season, Caulfield withdrew, and a second University team was quickly arranged to take its place for the 1919 season.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] The two University teams were known as University A and University B, later becoming the modern day 'University Blues' and 'University Blacks'.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] University B contested only the 1919 season, with a Melbourne Juniors team established for 1920; University A contested the 1919 and 1920 seasons, reaching the grand final both years before dropping out.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] West Melbourne faced multiple heavy losses in 1920, including a 197-point loss against Carlton District and a 229-point loss against St Kilda District.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] The club left the competition at the end of the season, and were replaced by Essendon Juniors.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] In 1925, the VJFL was renamed as the **VFL seconds**, later known more commonly as the **VFL reserves**.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] Following the change, the seconds clubs still operated as distinct stand-alone clubs at this time, rather than coming directly under the influence of their senior clubs.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] This changed over the following decades, with all of the seconds teams gradually being subsumed by their senior counterparts.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] Melbourne won the 1931, 1932, 1933, 1934 and 1935 premierships - the only time in VFL/AFL history (seniors or reserves) that a club has won five grand finals in a row.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] History was made in 1991, with the Brisbane Bears winning the reserves premiership − the first non-Victorian club to win a VFL/AFL premiership in any grade.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] The Victorian State Football League was established at the end of 1991 to take over administration of football in Victoria from the Australian Football League, which was now becoming preoccupied with administration of the game nationally.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] The VSFL ran the AFL reserves competition from 1992 until 1999, which was also referred as the VSFL in its first few years.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] At the end of 1994, the VSFL also took over administration of the Victorian Football Association (VFA) competition (which was renamed the Victorian Football League in 1996).
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] Following the 1999 season, the AFL reserves was merged into the Victorian Football League.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] Such a merger had first been proposed as early as 1980, and a formal attempt to enact the merger for the 1995 season was defeated after strong opposition from the clubs.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] South Melbourne was relocated to Sydney at the end of the 1981 VFL season, after which the club continued to play in the VFL/AFL reserves as Sydney.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] The Brisbane Bears competed for four years between 1989 and 1992, winning their only premiership at any grade in 1991.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] After their merger with Fitzroy at the end of 1996, the Brisbane Lions did not compete in the competition.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] No teams from South Australia or Western Australia ever competed in the VFL/AFL reserves.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] South Melbourne relocated to Sydney in 1982 was renamed Sydney Swans in 1983.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] Footscray was renamed Western Bulldogs in 1997.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] A number of notable players competed solely in the reserves competition.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] Shane Warne, considered to be one of the greatest bowlers in the history of cricket, played a single game for St Kilda in 1988: he was erroneously listed in the Record as Trevor Warne, and played in the Under-19s for the remainder of the season.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] Former St Kilda number one ticket holder John Moran also played for the reserves side.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] John Bourke, a Collingwood forward, infamously shoved an umpire and then attacked a fan among other incidents during a game in 1985, leading to a suspension of ten years plus 16 games, equivalent to 240 matches.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-reserves] Geelong won the most reserves premierships, with a total of 13.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] The **AFL National Championships** is an annual Australian national underage representative Australian rules football tournament.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] Since taking over as national governing body in 1995, the AFL has gradually restructured the competition into a primary junior pathway for its fully professional national club competition.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] The National Championships grew out of the **Teal Cup** which began in Brisbane in 1953 as a junior representative competition between the Australian states of Queensland and New South Wales.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] It was rebranded in 1976 to reflect its expansion to include representative teams from each Australian state and mainland territory, rotated between host cities.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] The current competition is contested as a hybrid representative format.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] The best players from the academy competitions (AFL club feeder teams) combine to form an 'Allies' team in conjunction with South Australia, Western Australia and two Victoria teams—Metro (Melbourne Metropolitan Area) and Country—to contest the division 1 tournament.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] Originally known as the **Teal Cup**, it was first held in Brisbane, Queensland in 1953 as a junior representative competition between the Australian states of Queensland and New South Wales.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] It was an annual match between the two states, the winners would possess a trophy donated by the Teal family of Queensland.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] Members of the Australian National Football Council, most notably Victorian representative Bruce Andrew, assisted in the establishment the competition in its early days.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] The Australian Capital Territory was the first other side to enter in 1973.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] With the addition of teams from each Australian state and mainland territory in 1976, the tournament was rebranded as the **National Championships** and rotated between host cities.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] The championships were split into two divisions with the strongest states including Victoria (later split into two sides: Vic Metro and Vic Country) comprising Division 1.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] Papua New Guinea was the first other country to field a team in 1979.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] In the absence of a national league, and less regular senior competition, it grew into one of the most important competitions in the country.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] Early on it was an Under-17 competition, however the age limit has been progressively increased and separate junior championships added for Under-15 level (commencing as the **Shell Cup**, now the **AFL National Development Championships**) from the 1970s onwards.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] It was a major talent pathway for underage players outside Victoria to the VFL.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] As part of the AFL Commission's role as national governing body, the Victorian TAC Cup competition was restructured in 1992 to become the primary pathway to the AFL.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] As a result, representative development sides from NSW/ACT and Tasmania for a time have played in that competition instead.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] However, in recent years, the National Championships has regained its status as a primary AFL recruitment pathway as the growth of the sport outside Victoria has accelerated.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] The division 2 competition was replaced by the Under-19 Academy Series in 2017, with teams from the 4 Queensland and NSW AFL clubs' academies in addition to Northern Territory and Tasmania state teams.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] The entire competition was changed to under-19s in 2021 (the competition has previously operated under-17s and under-18s competitions).
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] With there being no representative football at senior level since 1999, the National Championships are one of the few opportunities for players to play for their state or territory.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] Players typically share the senior team's guernsey (with the exception of Victorian teams, which play in variations of the state team guernsey—Vic Metro has a light blue Big V insignia, while Vic Country plays in a reverse white with navy Big V).
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] The best players from the academy competition then combine to form an 'Allies' team in conjunction with South Australia, Western Australia and two Victoria teams, Metro (Melbourne Metropolitan Area) and Country to contest the division 1 tournament.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] The winner of the 2024 division 1 tournament was Vic Metro, defeating Vic Country 12.13.85 to 13.6.84.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] The **Larke Medal** is awarded to the best player in Division 1 of the competition.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] It is named in honour of a junior footballer, Michael Larke, who was killed in a bus crash while attending a trial match for New South Wales.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] The **Hunter Harrison Medal** is awarded to the best player in Division 2 and is named in honour of a former president and life member of the Northern Territory Football League, Hunter Harrison, who played a major role in the development of the AFL Youth Championships.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] Each tournament, an underage All-Australian team is named; an MVP is also named for each team.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] Since 2017, the AFL has replaced state and territory representative teams with an academy division consisting of its QLD and NSW AFL Club sides: GWS Giants, Brisbane Lions, Gold Coast Suns and Sydney Swans.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-under-18-championships] The tournament is currently sponsored by the National Australia Bank, having previously been sponsored by Caltex and the Commonwealth Bank.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] The **NAB AFL Women's Under-18 Championships** are the annual national Australian rules football championships for women players aged 18 years or younger.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] The competition is seen as one of the main pathways towards being drafted into a team in the professional AFL Women's competition (AFLW).
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] Originally known as the *AFL Youth Girls National Championship*, the competition has teams of players representing their states and territories in a round robin tournament.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] The tournament is currently sponsored by the National Australia Bank.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] The winner of the 2019 tournament was Vic Metro.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] A 2008 series between the Queensland and Victoria teams was the predecessor to a national state-based competition for young female footballers.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] The inaugural competition was conducted in September 2010, in Craigieburn, Victoria.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] Six teams competed: Western Australia, South Australia, Queensland, a combined New South Wales and Australian Capital Territory side (NSW/ACT), and two Victorian squads.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] These were divided into two pools—first: an AFL Victoria Development squad combined with an East section, which consisted of NSW/ACT and Queensland players; and West, made up of players from South Australia, Western Australia, and Victoria.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] Teams played three regular games against the sides from the opposite pool before a finals series.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] Several team changes occurred in 2012 and 2013.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] In 2012, the Victorian team was split into Victoria Metro and Victoria Country.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] A combined Northern Territory–Tasmania team known as the Thunder Devils and an Indigenous Australian side called the Woomeras entered the tournament in 2014.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] In 2021 the Woomeras were joined by the *Medleys*, a multicultural under-17 representative program.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] AFL Women's, a national women's league which was inaugurated in 2017, allowed the championships to become a formalised pathway competition to the national league.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] Consequently the name of the competition was changed to AFL Women's Under 18 Championships, having previously been known as the AFL Under 18 Youth Girls Championships.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] Changes were also made to tournament structure.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] The tournament was played over two rounds; in the first round, South Australia, Tasmania and the Northern Territory played in a separate division.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] The best players from the states combined to form an Allies team, which competed in the second round against the other states (the Woomeras did not compete).
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] In 2018, a similar Eastern Allies team was established (made up of NSW/ACT and Tasmania players), bringing the total number of teams to 10.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s-under-18-championships] There was no championships staged in 2020 due to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic, which caused the 2021 tournament to have an increased age eligibility by one year (under-19).
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The AFLW is the second most attended women's football competition in Australia (behind A-League Women) and one of the most popular women's football competitions in the world.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Its average attendance in 2019 of 6,262 per game made it the second-highest of any domestic women's football competition.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Its record attendance of 53,034 for the 2019 AFL Women's Grand Final was until 2020 the highest match attendance for women's sport in Australia.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Since launch, the AFLW has attracted an audience of more than 1 million attendees and 2 million viewers and has managed to maintain high interest while moving to primarily ticketed and subscription broadcasting models since the 2021 season.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] It consistently ranks in the top three (alongside cricket and netball) most-watched women's sporting competitions in Australia.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The league receives international interest, particularly in Ireland, where it has begun to attract a significant television audience due to the ongoing recruitment of Irish Gaelic football stars.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] However, it was reported in mid-2023 that data revealed a significant drop in attendances for the seventh season of the women's league compared to the first season.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] While men playing Australian rules football is documented back to 1858, women's games have only been documented back to 1917, and the first lasting women's league was formed in 1981.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Women's participation in the sport and the prevalence of women's leagues continued to grow into the 21st century.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] In 2010, the AFL commissioned a report into the state of women's football around the country.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Following the report, the AFL Commission began working toward the establishment of a national women's league, choosing to establish women's teams in AFL clubs rather than form separate clubs.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The first on-field step towards the competition took place in early 2013, when the AFL announced an exhibition match to be played between women's teams representing Melbourne and Western Bulldogs in June of that year.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] On 15 May 2013, the first women's draft was held, establishing the playing lists for the two clubs in the forthcoming exhibition match.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The match played on 29 June 2013 marked the first time two women's sides had competed under the banners of AFL clubs.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] A crowd of 7,518 watched the historic match, which Melbourne won by 35 points.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The exhibition match became a series between the clubs, with another game played in 2014 and two played in 2015, the last of which – on 16 August 2015 – was the first women's AFL game to be broadcast on free-to-air television.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] It attracted an average audience of 175,000, surpassing the 114,000 average audience for the AFL men's clash of the previous day, between Adelaide and Essendon.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The success of these exhibition matches prompted the AFL to accelerate its plans for a nationwide women's competition, announcing a preferred start date of 2017.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Prior to this, the league had announced only aspirational plans to have the women's competition established by 2020.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The already-planned 2016 exhibition series was expanded at this time, with a total of ten matches to be played in venues across the country and featuring a range of new temporary representative teams.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] In 2016, the AFL opened a process for existing clubs to tender applications to join the new competition.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The 18 clubs in the men's league had until 29 April 2016 to place a bid for a licence, with 13 clubs making bids: Adelaide, Brisbane, Carlton, Collingwood, Fremantle, Geelong, Greater Western Sydney, Melbourne, North Melbourne, Richmond, St Kilda, West Coast, and Western Bulldogs.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The AFL's preferred distribution of clubs was four clubs from Victoria and one each from New South Wales, Queensland, South Australia, and Western Australia.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The inaugural teams were announced on 8 June 2016.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Adelaide, Brisbane, and Greater Western Sydney were the only teams to bid in their respective states and were granted licences to compete in 2017.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Both Western Australian clubs made bids, with Fremantle's bid chosen ahead of the bid from West Coast.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Eight Victorian clubs made bids: Melbourne, Western Bulldogs, Carlton and Collingwood were successful, with Geelong, North Melbourne, Richmond and St Kilda being unsuccessful but granted provisional licences.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Details about the branding of the league were released in the second half of 2016.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] On 15 September 2016, the AFL announced that the league would be named "AFL Women's" or AFLW for short, with the logo being unveiled on 19 September 2016.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The logo is a stylised rendition of an Australian rules football ground goal square and goal posts, drawn from a perspective that resembles a "W".
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] On 10 October 2016, the National Australia Bank was named as the league's naming rights sponsor.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The first premiership game was played at Ikon Park on Friday, 3 February 2017.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The AFL had initially planned to host the game at Melbourne's Olympic Park Oval, with a capacity of just 7,000, but was forced to change to Ikon Park due to overwhelming interest and a need for more seating.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The match was deemed a "lockout" with a capacity crowd of 24,568 in attendance, with estimates of a few thousand left outside.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Gillon McLachlan, the AFL's CEO, personally apologised to those who missed out.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The game was also a great success on TV, attracting a national audience of 896,000, including 593,000 metropolitan free-to-air viewers, 180,000 regional free-to-air viewers, and 123,000 on Fox Footy.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The Melbourne metropolitan audience of 424,000 was on par with that of Friday-night AFL men's matches.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The inaugural season concluded with the Grand Final held on Saturday, 25 March 2017.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The Adelaide Crows were crowned the league's first premiers after defeating the minor premiers, the Brisbane Lions.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The scoreline read Adelaide 4.11 (35) def.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The remaining AFL clubs would join the league in the follow years, with two clubs added in the 2019 season, four in 2020, and the last four in 2022.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The 10 AFL clubs not originally participating in the competition were invited to bid for inclusion, with priority given to the five clubs that had submitted unsuccessful bids to participate in the inaugural season.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The deadline to lodge submissions was 16 June 2017.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The only clubs not to bid were Port Adelaide and Sydney.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] North Melbourne worked with AFL Tasmania to craft its bid, with the club aiming to play home matches in Melbourne, Hobart, and Launceston, and also to select half of its playing list from Tasmania.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] A final decision on which clubs would be admitted to the competition was expected by the end of July 2017, but was delayed several times.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] On 27 September 2017, the AFL announced that Geelong and North Melbourne had been selected to enter the competition in 2019.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] North Melbourne retained its commitment to playing matches in Tasmania.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The league then added four teams in 2020, with the AFL selecting Gold Coast, Richmond, St Kilda and West Coast to join the competition.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The growth in clubs for the 2019 season was accompanied by the introduction of an American-style conference structure, which was abandoned after the 2020 season in favour of the traditional single ladder.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the 2020 season was curtailed and eventually cancelled without a premiership awarded.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] On 12 August 2021, the final four AFL clubs (Essendon, Hawthorn, Port Adelaide and Sydney) were granted licenses, and the league's seventh season in 2022 was the first to feature all 18 AFL clubs.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] North Melbourne became the first expansion team, founded after the inaugural season, to win a premiership, when the Kangaroos defeated Brisbane by 30 points in the 2024 decider, following this up with a 40 point victory in the 2025 Grand Final rematch.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The competition's 18 teams are based across five states of Australia.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Ten are based in Victoria (nine in the Melbourne metropolitan area), and New South Wales, Queensland, South Australia and Western Australia have two teams each, while a team from Tasmania will enter the AFLW at a date to be confirmed.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory are the only states or territories not to have AFLW teams.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Below are the venues that hosted during the 2025 season.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The club's playing lists were constructed from scratch through the later stages of 2016.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] All participants in the 2017 season were required to be over the age of 17.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Initially, clubs were asked to nominate a list of desired players, with the AFL assigning two of these "marquee" players to each club.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] In addition, clubs were able to sign a number of players with existing connections to the club, or with arrangements for club-sponsored work or study.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] This number varied for each club, in an attempt to equitably spread talent across the teams.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] In addition, clubs were required to recruit two "rookies" – people with no Australian rules football experience in the previous three-year period.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The majority of players were later recruited through the 2016 AFL Women's draft.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The remaining list spots were filled with free-agent signings in the week following the draft.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] In total, clubs have 27 active listed players in addition to injury replacements signed to take the spot of long-term injury-affected players.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Player salaries are determined by collective bargaining agreement with each club's total payments being determined by a salary cap.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] A significant gender pay gap exists between AFL and the AFLW, with the average wage in the women's league being only 16% of that in the men's league as of 2023.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Prior to the commencement of the home-and-away season teams are paired off to play an exhibition trial match.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] In 2017, these matches took place during varying weeks of January.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] For the first two seasons of competition, the home-and-away season was operated on a single table, and seven matches were played by each of the eight teams.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The two highest-placed teams at the conclusion of the home-and-away season qualified for the Grand Final match, in the absence of a longer finals series.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] With the addition of two extra teams in 2019, the AFL Women's home-and-away season introduced conferences, a concept not common in Australian sports.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The top-two teams from the respective conferences qualified to the preliminary finals, with the first-ranked team in Conference A meeting the second-ranked team in Conference B and the opposite employed for the other preliminary final.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The winners of those matches then met in the Grand Final.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The use of conferences was retained in 2020, along with the inclusion of four additional teams.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The 14 teams were split into two conferences of seven, with teams playing each other team in their conference once.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The top-four teams in each conference qualified for the finals series.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The first round of the finals consisted of four knockout finals, with teams from opposite conferences playing against each other, first in Conference A versus fourth in Conference B, and so on.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] This left a final four of North Melbourne, Fremantle, Carlton, and Melbourne, with two rounds of finals to be played.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] At this point, the season was abandoned due to the COVID-19 pandemic, with no 2020 premier.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] In 2021, the league reverted to a single 14-team ladder.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Each team played 9 matches, with the top six qualifying for a three-week finals series.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] All finals are knockouts, with the top-two teams having a bye in the first round of the finals.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Since 2022 (S7) the competition has been contested by 18 teams, and the finals series has expanded to eight teams and is played under the AFL final eight system that has been in use in the men's competition since the 2000 season.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] On 21 August 2023, incoming AFL chief executive Andrew Dillon announced that the AFLW will receive equal prize money to the AFL.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The prize money for AFLW players will almost double, going from $623,922 to $1.1 million to split between the top 8 teams.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] In 2018, the Western Bulldogs and Carlton women's teams held the first Pride game, to celebrate gender diversity, promote inclusion for LGBTIQA+ players, and to help stamp out homophobia.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] St Kilda and Melbourne held a Pride Match in 2020, and the first full AFLW Pride Round was held in 2021.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] An Indigenous Round was established in 2021.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] This round acknowledges the significant contribution of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander women and girls to Australian football and the broader community.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Each team wears a guernsey especially designed to celebrate Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander culture, and the Dreamtime match is played between Richmond and Essendon.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] An AFLW Indigenous Round Honouree is announced for each season.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The league peaked at an average attendance of 6,828 in its inaugural season and a record 53,034 attended the 2019 Grand Final.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Admission was free prior to 2022, when the AFLW introduced reserved ticketing at $10 admission per match, which was later increased.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] In mid-2023, data revealed a significant drop in average attendances for the seventh season compared to the first season.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Taking into account the greater number of games played, total attendance was still growing, just spread over three times as many matches.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The league's choice of venues has been criticised, with many of the AFL's premium venues, such as Victoria's Melbourne Cricket Ground and Docklands Stadium, not used for blockbuster AFLW matches.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The league has been cited as preferring the atmosphere of fuller smaller venues rather than emptier larger venues, particularly for its television broadcasting.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] In its inaugural 2017 season, all matches were televised live by affiliate partners the Seven Network and Fox Footy.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] As part of the initial broadcast deal, the free-to-air carrier Seven broadcast one Saturday-night game per week as standard, in addition to the league's opening match and Grand Final.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Pay TV network Fox Footy televised all premiership season matches, including simulcasts of the Seven-hosted matches other than the Grand Final.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The two television networks covered the costs of broadcasting these matches, with no licensing fee payable to the league in exchange.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] *Fearless: The Inside Story of the AFLW* debuted on Disney+ in 2022, the docu-series followed several AFLW clubs through the course of the 2022 season.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] In July 2023 *The Age* reported that AFLW viewer numbers were down 70% from the debut season, blaming a combination of scheduling, poor quality venues and broadcast quality, and "football fatigue".
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The AFLW has attracted an audience of more than 1 million attendees and 2 million viewers and has managed to maintain high interest despite moving to primarily ticketed and subscription broadcasting models from the 2021 season.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] It consistently ranks in the top three (alongside cricket and netball) most watched women's sporting competitions in Australia.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The league receives international interest, particularly in Ireland where it has begun to attract a significant television audience due to the ongoing recruitment of Gaelic football stars.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The official internet/mobile broadcast partner of the AFL is BigPond, part of Telstra.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The company hosts the league website and those of each of the eight participation clubs.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The AFL has retained digital broadcast rights to matches in the league's inaugural season and will stream all matches live and free on the league website and mobile app.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Since 2021, Kayo Sports has streamed all AFLW matches live and on demand in Australia.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Outside Australia, the inaugural season is available on Watch AFL.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The National Australia Bank is the league's inaugural and (as of 2022) current naming-rights partner.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] All playing and training equipment, as well as all licensed apparel and hats for the league's clubs, are manufactured by Cotton On.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Other 2017 league sponsors included Wolf Blass, Chemist Warehouse, and Kellogg's.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Official match-day attire, together with other club merchandise, is sold through the AFL's stores and website, as well through the clubs and some retailers.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Prior to the creation of the league, the AFL ran four years of exhibition matches between sides representing Melbourne and Western Bulldogs.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] In 2016, the series was expanded to multiple teams from around the country.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The best and fairest award determined in the same way as the Brownlow Medal for men, with umpires awarding three, two, and one votes to the best three players in each game, and suspended players are ineligible.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] The MVP award is voted on by the players' peers, in a similar method to the Leigh Matthews Trophy for men.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/afl-women-s] Each week, the senior coach of each club gives five votes to the player they consider to be best on ground in the game in which their team plays, four to the second-best, and so on to one for the fifth-best.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] The AFL held two official Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season AFLX competitions featuring senior AFL clubs and players, in 2018 and 2019, but these were unpopular with spectators and did not return in 2020.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] The variation continues to be promoted by the AFL Commission as a participation sport in development regions and areas, and particularly where full-sized cricket grounds are not available.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] Since the COVID-19 pandemic, AFLX has been merged with AFL 9s and retained only the X brand, co-branding AFL 9s as Junior X, Youth X and Senior X and aligning it with the more widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] The rules of the game differed from standard Australian rules football in some significant ways.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] The game was played on a rectangular soccer-sized pitch, allowing matches to be hosted by stadiums that usually lacked the suitable field dimensions for Australian rules football.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] AFLX was first trialled at Arden Street Oval in January 2017.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] Two months later, it was trialed at was first trialled on a soccer pitch at Lakeside Stadium in a match between the Port Melbourne Football Club and Coburg Football Club.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] AFLX pre-season competition was launched by AFL chief executive officer Gillon McLachlan at Docklands Stadium on 6 February 2018.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] McLachlan said that AFLX would help promote football internationally.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] The 2018 competition attracted more than 40,000 fans to tournaments in Adelaide, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] In Melbourne, TV ratings were reported as "modest" by AFL standards, with the three events drawing an average five-city metro audience of over 120,000 on Channel Seven's secondary channels.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] The AFL made several rule tweaks midway through the second season in attempt to make it higher scoring by inflating the scoring points for behinds from 1 to 2, goals from 6 to 12 and Super Goals from 10 to 20.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] Whitten Legends Game was also played under "EJX" (modified version of AFLX named after E J Whitten) at AAMI Park in Melbourne.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] It attracted just 6,000 spectators, the lowest in the series history.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] AFLX did not return as a senior AFL competition in 2020, as AFL had a greater focus on AFLW.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] Post the COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased the number of players to 9, effectively merging AFLX with AFL 9s and aligning with the widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] The reception to the two AFL pre-season competitions among fans and the media was mostly poor, with ABC Radio Grandstand journalist Richard Hinds being particularly savage in labelling it a "hollow, unappealing, pressure-free, atmosphere-deficient, oval-in-a-rectangle hole yawn-fest".
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/aflx] Con Stavros of RMIT's school of Economics, Finance and Marketing, expressed doubts about the potential of AFLX to export Australian rules football but acknowledged that using rectangular playing fields instead of the standard cricket ones would make such expansion easier.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] A **guernsey** (also called a **jumper**) is a type of shirt worn by Australian rules footballers.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] It is typically sleeveless, although long sleeves may also be worn.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] The typical guernsey features the player's number on the back, the colours of the player's team, and the team logo.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] Sponsor logos may also appear on the guernsey.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] Unlike sports such as soccer and American football, the surnames of Australian rules footballers do not appear on their shirts (with the exception of International Rules football, which is a hybrid code).
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] Australian rules football is unique in referring to the player's shirt as a "guernsey", with most other sports referring to their respective uniforms as a "jersey".
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] As an extension of this tradition, the expression "to get a guernsey" is a metaphor for being selected for something or gaining recognition for an achievement.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] The first footballers often wore cricket whites during matches with teams distinguished by wearing coloured ribbons and caps.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] By the 1870s, footballers started to wear more rugged and robust woollen navy jumpers called Guernseys which traced their origins to the Channel Islands off the coast of France.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] It is from this garment that the modern football guernsey takes its name.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] By the 1880s, most footballers were wearing lace-up jerkins made from canvas and leather.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] A guernsey could be worn underneath the jerkin to provide the player added warmth.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] By World War 1, the lace up jerkin was dispensed with by most VFL teams, although this form of clothing was used in other leagues such as the SANFL until 2001.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] By the 1910s and 1920s, modern knitting and dying techniques had made it easier to produce woollen jumpers in varying patterns and colours.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] Collars were added to the jumpers and sleeveless options became popular amongst footballers.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] Although wool had been used as the main fabric of choice, most guernseys were changed to the much cheaper acrylic in the 1980s.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] In the late 1990s, collars were removed from football guernseys and manufacturers began making the clothing by using modern polyester fabrics using sublimated dying techniques.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] During the 1970s, VFL teams began sewing the VFL logo and sponsor logos on their guernseys.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] Clash and preseason guernseys came into effect during the 1990s due to the growing demand by fans and broadcasters to make football easier to watch by making matches fully “light vs dark” rather than the simple dark shorts vs white shorts.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] Most AFL clubs wear a home guernsey for a majority of games (specifically games that are played at their home ground) and a clash guernsey for away games where the team’s guernsey clashes in colour with the other team’s.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] The most common type of clash guernsey is a colour swap where, for example, a team with white stripes on a mostly black jumper changes to black stripes on a mostly white jumper.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] From 2003 to 2007, AFL teams wore a heritage guernsey which was a recreation of a guernsey from previous seasons.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] Every year since 2014, AFL clubs have designed a special guernsey in honour of the annual Indigenous Round/Sir Doug Nicholls Round.
[src:guernsey-australian-rules-football/guernsey-australian-rules-football] These guernseys, worn by every club in the AFL, feature Indigenous-Australian artwork and are sometimes designed by past or even present players of the club.
